{\n "cells": [\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "# Multi-Layer Perceptron for Traffic Object Detection",\n "\n",\n "This Jupyter notebook implements a comprehensive multi-layer perceptron (MLP) model for detecting traffic objects. The notebook includes steps from data exploration to model evaluation with professional-grade visualizations. \n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "## Table of Contents",\n "\n",\n "1. [Introduction](#Introduction)\n",\n "2. [Data Exploration](#Data-Exploration)\n",\n "3. [Data Preprocessing](#Data-Preprocessing)\n",\n "4. [Model Building](#Model-Building)\n",\n "5. [Model Training](#Model-Training)\n",\n "6. [Evaluation](#Evaluation)\n",\n "7. [Visualizations](#Visualizations)\n",\n "8. [Conclusion](#Conclusion)\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "## Introduction",\n "\n",\n "In this notebook, we will explore the implementation of a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) for detecting traffic objects in various conditions. The effectiveness of the MLP will be examined through different stages, including data preparation and evaluation.\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "## Data Exploration",\n "\n",\n "Data exploration is critical to understanding the characteristics of the data. Here we will load our dataset and examine the first few records.\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "code",\n "execution_count": null,\n "metadata": {},\n "outputs": [],\n "source": [\n "import pandas as pd\n",\n "\n",\n "# Load dataset\n",\n "data = pd.read_csv('traffic_data.csv')\n",\n "data.head()\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "## Data Preprocessing",\n "\n",\n "Data preprocessing includes handling missing values, feature scaling, and splitting the dataset into training and testing sets.\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "code",\n "execution_count": null,\n "metadata": {},\n "outputs": [],\n "source": [\n "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",\n "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",\n "\n",\n "# Handle missing values\n",\n "data.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)\n",\n "\n",\n "# Feature scaling\n",\n "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",\n "X = data.drop('target', axis=1)\n",\n "y = data['target']\n",\n "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n",\n "\n",\n "# Split the dataset\n",\n "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "markdown",\n "metadata": {},\n "source": [\n "## Model Building",\n "\n",\n "Here we build our MLP model using TensorFlow/Keras.\n"\n ]\n },\n {\n "cell_type": "code",\n "execution_count": null,\n "metadata": {},\n "outputs": [],\n "source": [\n "from tensorflow import keras\n",\n "from tensorflow.keras import layers\n",\n "\n",\n "# Create MLP model\n",\n "model = keras.Sequential([\n",\n "    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],)),\n",\n "    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),\n",\n "    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')\n",\n "])
\n